  Indian architecture is a rich and diverse tapestry reflecting the country's extensive cultural and historical heritage. From the urban planning of the Indus Valley Civilization, evident in the cities of Harappa and Mohenjo-Daro, to the advanced drainage systems and grid layouts, early Indian architecture showcased remarkable ingenuity. The Maurya and Gupta periods saw the rise of Buddhist architecture with iconic stupas like the Great Stupa at Sanchi and rock-cut caves at Ajanta and Ellora. Hindu temple architecture flourished with styles such as the Nagara in the north and Dravidian in the south, exemplified by the intricate carvings and towering gopurams of temples like Khajuraho and Brihadeeswarar. The Mughal period introduced Persian influences, resulting in grand structures like the Taj Mahal and Fatehpur Sikri. Colonial rule brought European styles, seen in edifices like the Victoria Memorial and Rashtrapati Bhavan. Modern Indian architecture continues to evolve, blending traditional elements with contemporary design, as seen in cities like Chandigarh and modern skyscrapers across metropolitan areas. This continuous evolution highlights the dynamic and adaptive nature of Indian architectural traditions.





